The full version is way fun. With unlimited planets you can go as nuts as your device will handle watching the hypnotic progression of the planets orbiting. There are however some points that could be improved. Frequently the habitable zone shown when the setting is enabled is off, sometimes extremely off for big bad blue stars that have ate a bunch. Black holes are UGE at the start buf if you lower the mass and then raise the mass they become tiny and that can't be undone until restart. At high speeds sometimes planets will go through each other ignoring the collision but gravity will fling them fast enough they are either forgotten soon after or so far away they get floating point imprecision. Some suggestions I have are nebula makers, place habitable tool, red and brown dwarfs, neutron stars should result from blue giant novas, gas giants collapsing to stars, more tweakable properties should be exposed from the save files, increase and decrease age tool that can effect the development of planets and stars as well as being able to make little stars go supernova and produce a dwarf, a way to make a stable orbit around stuff that are impossible to select. Good time killer though.

I love Pocket Universe. I've only been using it for like a week now and already I'm in waist deep in intelligent life nurseries and celestial body gladiatorial arenas. I only had two gameplay gripes, which is that a planet at orbit cannot sustain life (flew too close to the sun/big freeze) and that when moving a body it can't be put into orbit. But the game is still worth it if you are even a little interested in astronomy, the formation of bodies in the universe, or massive-scale physics simulators. The only thing I could ask for is an extension of the life mechanics. I actually was a little disappointed when my "space-faring" people couldn't visit the other planets I made for them, or populate other planets to survive more than one extinction event, or acknowledge other intelligent life in the neighborhood. I would pay more money to have these features, and I hope the devs read this because I would really pay to have these features. Life is the closest thing to an endgame or conflict in Pocket Universe, and improving those features would improve the whole game noticeably. And it's already a great game, so download it and leave a review asking for the same thing!

While I wish I could say this game is perfect, it still has quite a few flaws that need to be addressed. Most of the issues I've faced appear to be bugs, which I hope means a swift fix. Saving is a mandatory action at least once per minute, or else facing a sudden seize of U.I. controls, effectively rendering the game unplayable until restarted. Speaking of saving, that feature only seems to half-work. Black holes never save, so when I load a save, black holes which kept my galaxy stable are now missing, throwing the universe into utter chaos. 3 hours of perfecting the way stars orbit black holes, while planets orbit said stars, all wasted in the blink of an eye. Not to mention, the save feature has on occasion completely failed, leading me to an empty sandbox when I load the save. Finally, the graphics limit and navigation both need work. Having too many asteroids will cause the game to lag drastically, until I enter the management system and hand-pluck them out of existence. Speaking of, moving from star to star is a pain, I wish there was some kind of minimap, or further zoom functionality. Without these, moving around my universe can take forever, especially if I can't quite remember where I placed a star or what its name was. Aside from these issues, I absolutely love the idea and the game play, and the ideas the developers implemented have gone spectacularly for me. I'd like to spend more time going over everything I love. Perhaps in an edit when I have less criticism.

It's a very nice game. It allows you to create simulated galaxies and star systems, and even lets you have s little fun with stars, black holes, wormholes, and more; it's always fun to throw a blue giant across the map through a wormhole hardly comparable in size!   However, there are some flaws you should consider before purchasing, and while they shouldn't be so influential as to completely derail your decision to buy it, it's still some things you should know.  One issue I have had is that objects sometimes don't orbit what I direct it to orbit; say I place down a moon and set it to orbit a planet. Sometimes the moon just stays in place, or even catches gravity quickly and crashes into the planet. Yay, cataclysm! Unfortunately, I have to delete the moon, or recreate the planet.  Another problem is that placing satellites completely destroys the map in terms of responsiveness. Once you add a satellite, you can no longer access the log, place down a planet, or even open the pause menu. Thus, you'll have to close the game, reopen, and delete the satellite.  Despite this, I would still very much recommend you purchase this game, especially if you're into astronomy or even just smashing stuff together. I hope the developers may address these issues, and for those of you who purchase and support the devs, I hope you enjoy the game. :)

Anyone remember playing that game Gravitation back in the 80s? Well, Pocket Universe is the super evolution of that game. Graphics are simply stunning, gameplay is engaging yet there is still much room for growth, and the variety of celestial objects to unlock is large enough to keep the replay value at an acceptable level.    Suggestions for improvement:  The UI needs some serious overhaul. Using two finger swipe to move the map or rotate view based on toggling a control is cumbersome at best. This unfortunately mars the game considerably as there are numerous other games out there that have tackled the same problem in a far more matured form.  A game like this needs to show the total mass in your current system as well as the makeup of the mass in some general categories aside from just water and rock. We should at least be able to see universe makeup at a high level by percentage of naturally occurring periodic elements (e.g. carbon, oxygen, iron, plutonium, etc.).  This game desperately needs a means of auto-generating meteors based on user settings. Having to place 10000+ meteors by hand does get old, though this really only applies if you're trying to build a system without placing any planets or Stars directly.   Finally, and this is really a question, is it possible to actually create a star from placing enough meteors? I've been playing a game where I've only placed meteors and have thus created numerous massive planets yet have not been able to develop a star. Is it just an issue of throwing enough mass into the system or does one actually need to place a star if one wants a star? If one does have to place a star then that is another item for improvement. We should be able to develop a full system simply by placing enough meteors. On the hand, if it is possible to create a star only for meteors then this makes the aforementioned suggestion of needing a means to auto-generate meteors that much more necessary.   Bottom line though, this is an awesome game worth paying for the premium version. I cannot wait to see what updates are forthcoming.
